07415nam a22010575i 9783110675160DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2021938138  a97831106751607 a10.1515/97831106751602doi  a(DE-B1597)535963  a(OCoLC)1266228269  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aP284b.W49 2021 7aLAN0090602bisacsh04a420  aET 750qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/28029:00aWhy is ‘Why’ Unique? :bIts Syntactic and Semantic Properties /ced. by Gabriela Soare. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (VI, 318 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Generative Grammar [SGG] ,x0167-4331 ;v14200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPart 1: Why in a Gbe language -- tReason questions as a complementizer domain phenomenon: Evidence from Ewe -- tPart 2: Towards a cartography of high and low reason adverbials -- tOn ‘why’ in situ in Northern Italian dialects: Evidence from Trevisan -- tWhy questions break the residual V2 restriction (in Basque and beyond) -- tIs German warum so special after all? -- tWhy in Dutch? On why-stripping and high and low adverbials -- tPart 3: Wh-in-Situ languages: Whys, hows, and whats -- tOn applicative Why-questions in Chinese -- tWhat-as-Why sentences in Cantonese -- tPart 4: Some syntactic aspects of how come -- tHow come questions and diary English -- tPart 5: A special class of why rhetorical questions: Semantics and pragmatics -- tWhy rhetorical questions? -- tPart 6: Why and the syntax-prosody interface -- tOn some special properties of why in syntax and prosody -- tIndex of subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhy is ‘Why’ Unique? Its Syntactic and Semantic Properties considers the behaviour of this peculiar wh-element across many different languages, including Ewe, Trevisan, Italian, Basque, German, Dutch, Cantonese, Mandarin, English and Hebrew. In ten original chapters, the authors explore various aspects of why-questions, such as the way why interacts with V2 constructions in Basque, with a subject clitic in Trevisan or how its morpho-syntactic make-up determines its merge position in Ewe, to mention but a few. Furthermore, a clear-cut distinction is established between high and low reason adverbials which are subsequently examined in why-stripping environments in Dutch. Beyond why proper, the book explores a special class of wh-expressions in some in-situ languages which give rise to unexpected why-construals with a touch of whining force. The objective is to explain the unusual syntactic position of these wh-expressions as well as their association with peculiar pragmatics. The questions are addressed for Cantonese: are what-initial sentences genuine questions? To what extent are Cantonese what-initial sentences similar to how-initial sentences in Mandarin? Beside these what-as-why questions, a special class of rhetorical questions, the doubly-marked interrogatives in Hebrew, come under scrutiny. Why is ‘why’ unique also concerns the interface with prosody and several experimental studies investigate precisely this aspect.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aGrammar, Comparative and generalxAdverbials. 4aAdjunkt. 4aSatzglied. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Syntax.2bisacsh  aHigh and Low Reasons Adjuncts.  aMerge Position.  aWhy-questions.  a‘What’ as Why-questions.1 aBocci, Giuliano, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonan, Caterina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuell, Leston Chandler, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCatasso, Nicholas, econtributor.4ct